 Aigent Pizza OS

A Visual Operating System for Distributed AI Agents

Aigent Pizza OS is an experimental interface for orchestrating AI agents across multiple machines using a human-readable control system.

Instead of traditional dashboards or command lines, Aigent uses a visual byte model inspired by an eight-slice pizza.

1 Byte = 8 Bits
1 Pizza = 8 Execution Modules

Each slice represents a functional execution layer inside an AI agent network.

The goal is to make distributed AI orchestration understandable, observable, and controllable by humans.

Built in under 24 hours during an AI Agent Hackathon.

---

# The Idea

Modern AI systems are becoming distributed, autonomous, opaque, and difficult to monitor.

Aigent Pizza OS explores a different model: visual system control.

The pizza interface acts as a human control surface for complex distributed systems.

System flow

User
↓
Pizza Interface (Byte Model)
↓
Agent Execution Layer
↓
Distributed Compute Nodes
↓
Telemetry + TimeCore

This allows operators to

• view system health
• monitor execution flows
• control agent behaviour
• observe distributed performance

---

# The Pizza Byte Model

A single pizza represents one byte of computational structure.

```
    1
```

128      2

64           4

```
32      8
     16
```

Each slice represents a functional system module.

Example mapping

Slice 1 — Agent orchestration
Slice 2 — Execution engine
Slice 3 — Memory layer
Slice 4 — Network communication
Slice 5 — Data ingestion
Slice 6 — Monitoring and telemetry
Slice 7 — Security and sovereignty
Slice 8 — TimeCore event system

This creates a human-friendly representation of system architecture.

